snippet.textDisplay: Bunch of fools in the comments that don’t really know this sport. His weight shouldn’t have mattered as the defending champion but his corner did him no favors, they weren’t accustomed to coaching as the champs. Why follow the contender around the ring catching jabs all night? As the champ he should’ve planted himself in the middle of the ring and demanded Joshua come in and when he did step inside to AJs right get low and look for body shots and overhand punches, any of his quick combinations when possible. The contender came in dancing around the entire ring and the champ chased him all night eating the reach differential. For what reason? He chased him until he was behind the score cards after several rounds and then he had no choice but to chase him and that’s when it started looking even worse since that opened him up to more abuse. AJ has mad discipline to know when to disengage with ARJ too he almost slipped up twice but he had the discipline (or fear flashbacks) to stick to his game plan and his corner didn’t fail him in this like ARJ’s. Too see no adjustment from ARJ’s side is sorry on their part and after all this THEN the weight becomes a problem but it shouldn’t have been a problem to begin with, once it did factor in it was way too late anyway. If there’s a third match and ARJ comes in 100lbs lighter that will not matter if AJ has the same plan and discipline. Yes ARJ will be able to chase him down better being lighter but unless he catches him just right AJ will stay ahead on the scorecards.

snippet.textDisplay: When you keep saying "No excuses" you kinda have to stop giving excuses in the same sentences to maintain your credibility. Just stop saying "I don't want to give any excuses." If you would have left that out, you could have just said "I lived it up too much because I took for granted that I had his number." More importantly, you should have known he would make adjustments and NEVER expect your opponent to do you the favor of catering to your style, especially a big man that's athletic and trained well enough to keep you on the end of the stick. I know Ruiz is the professional boxer. I'm not. I deal with different adversities. What I am sharing is a philosophy, and that is not to expect your adversities to cooperate with you because adversities are like Murphy's law, they always require your best efforts to contain them because they are always numerous and always working against you. Hence, the saying "Whatever can go wrong, will." When your adversity actually has a consciousness with the intent to defeat you, the last thing you can do is take your dominance for granted. Best of luck on the comeback.
